Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Missile Crisis
„Thirteen Days” („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Missile Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas in numerous countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it provides insights into current events – especially regarding the controversies surrounding a US national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy called his closest advisors together in the White House.
Aerial photographs of the region had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons deployment on Cuba.
The decisions made during the following thirteen days, and the decisions that could not be made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during these days.
Audio recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a major role in the production of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion panel to discuss the film as well as the crisis it addresses.
Participants in this panel included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Missile Crisis, the work "Essence of Decision", thirty years ago.
Moreover, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was also present.
Although the filmic treatment of the subject was criticized in various points, the participants in the discussion were able to agree that the film portrays the problems and pressure that President Kennedy faced as they actually were.
What conclusions can be drawn from the Cuban Crisis today?
Theodore Sorensen has summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in the event of a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately has to bear the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – civilian as well as military advisors – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be pointed out that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, communication channels must remain open.
Driving an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow understanding of the opponent's situation could prove disastrous.
· The United States is dependent on allies.
Kennedy acted this way because the NATO, further allies, and the opinion of the world had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
When it comes to life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to push him into an action.
The fact that a week passed during which all involved factors had been examined and weighed most carefully was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a time period for deliberation even exist today in view of the existing mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the highly criticized scenes of the film, McNamara explains to a warlike admiral that the naval blockade that Kennedy imposed on Cuba was mainly intended to send a signal to Chairman Khrushchev about Kennedy's intention, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Couldn't Kennedy have acted more calmly?
After all, the USA had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba only reflected this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed concern regarding the consequences that the stationing of Soviet missiles in Cuba would have had with respect to Berlin.
The pressure of atomic weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
Ultimately, "the Berlin crisis was resolved by the results of the Cuban crisis," claimed historian Ernest May.
"Soon it will be too late," was a widely circulated argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the missiles – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
A US force of about 180,000 men was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a blitz bombing, which would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. "It took me thirty years," said McNamara, "to find out that there were already atomic weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those 90 strategic nuclear warheads."
McNamara received this information on the occasion of a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He posed Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: "I knew about it.
And I explicitly recommended that nuclear weapons be used.
I knew that this would have led to the annihilation of Cuba.”
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba go up in smoke, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for the world revolution!
An invasion would thus have resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy government lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (a situation that often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion would "undoubtedly" have led to a Soviet atomic attack against the USA.
Chruschtschow's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: airplanes of the type U2 flying over Cuban airspace were shot at despite explicit instructions to the contrary from the chairman.
A difficult question to answer, which did not arise during this debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if the opponent had not been Chruschtschow, who distinguished himself during the crisis by more rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type of Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of nuclear weapons, this danger could one day become a reality.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of nuclear blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but quite realistic thought.
Harvard has launched a new Web site on the Internet, where the essential documents about the Cuban Missile Crisis as well as current nuclear threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
